a more targeted title would just be how to make a dashboard with bslib.

00:01:55.879 --> 00:01:56.879
Right.

00:01:56.879 --> 00:02:04.199
So you might have already heard about the R package bslib, which Shiny now depends on.

00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:11.839
And you might have already used it to basically upgrade the version of Bootstrap that Shiny

00:02:11.839 --> 00:02:14.800
uses underneath the hood.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:21.160
So kind of like the first main goal for bslib is to allow you to kind of seamlessly use

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:29.160
any version of Bootstrap and easily customize the CSS that comes with Bootstrap.

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:34.039
And we'll see a quick example of this a little bit later on, but kind of the meat of the

00:02:34.039 --> 00:02:42.399
talk today is going to be about how we've been kind of slowly been thinking about increasing

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:50.240
the scope of this bslib package into including sort of like be the new home for building

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:58.880
out like a modern UI toolkit that could replace not only Shiny, but Shiny dashboard as well.

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:05.720
And currently this includes at least like about a handful of components, including cards,

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:11.580
the development version of bslib now includes some sidebar layout stuff.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:20.860
We also have value boxes and accordions and page and layout helpers and a few other things.

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:25.339
And we haven't really started this work for Shiny for Python, but we're kind of talking

00:03:25.339 --> 00:03:31.660
about integrating this work into Shiny for Python, as well as the Shiny UI editor.

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:36.979
There was actually a release for the Shiny UI editor today that adds integrations for

00:03:36.979 --> 00:03:38.619
cards.

00:03:38.619 --> 00:03:43.860
But this is very much in the early stages where bslib is kind of leading the charge

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:49.160
in terms of building this stuff out for R, but we're hoping to be able to bring kind

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:56.059
of the same world of a UI toolkit to Python and the UI editor.

00:03:56.059 --> 00:03:57.860
All right.

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:03.899
So the easiest way to get started with bslib is to use one of its drop-in replacements

00:04:03.899 --> 00:04:07.020
for Shiny's page containers.

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:12.660
So the main difference here is like a difference in naming that embraces like autocompletes

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:14.500
and snake casing.

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:20.820
So you start off with creating your page container by saying page underscore, maybe fluid or

00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:24.859
fixed or nav bar.

00:04:24.859 --> 00:04:29.660
And this is just a basic fluid page with a level one header.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:32.059
All right.

00:04:32.059 --> 00:04:39.820
So page containers currently default to Bootstrap 5, basically because bslib currently defaults

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:45.100
to Bootstrap 5, and that's the most modern version of Bootstrap.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:51.579
But we're going to be a lot more aggressive than, say, Shiny would be about always updating

00:04:51.579 --> 00:04:54.700
to the most recent version of Bootstrap.

00:04:54.700 --> 00:05:01.660
So if you're using bslib in production, it's probably a good idea to pin the version of

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:07.220
Bootstrap to whatever the current version of Bootstrap is, so that when you go to upgrade

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:13.299
bslib in the future, you're not surprised by, you know, some Bootstrap-specific features

00:05:13.299 --> 00:05:21.339
that you are using that happen to break with a more modern version of Bootstrap.

00:05:21.339 --> 00:05:25.940
And then just quickly want to mention, you know, with this bstheme object, you have access

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:27.980
to boot swatch themes.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:33.899
So Bootstrap 5 came out with at least, like, a few new boot swatch themes.

00:05:33.899 --> 00:05:37.899
One example would be Quartz.

00:05:37.899 --> 00:05:45.059
And you may have also seen bslib's ability to do custom theming, where we make it pretty

00:05:45.059 --> 00:05:49.660
easy for you to just choose, like, the main colors and fonts, but there's also hundreds

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:54.980
of different theming variables that are exposed through Bootstrap.

00:05:55.019 --> 00:05:59.739
And if you've ever worked with, like, custom fonts, you may have noticed this font Google

00:05:59.739 --> 00:06:05.980
function, which makes custom fonts a lot easier, where it can automatically download cache

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:12.500
and import Google font files for you.

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:17.220
And so that's kind of, like, in a nutshell, how to do theming on the page level.

00:06:17.220 --> 00:06:22.019
But if you want to get more targeted with your theming, where you want, like, say, certain

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:28.140
headers or certain components to be styled a little bit differently than others or handle,

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:32.700
like, spacing between components and this sort of thing, it can be really helpful to

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:35.660
be aware of Bootstrap utility classes.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:41.220
So here I'm adding a class of text center and text primary to this header, so that I

00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:47.019
get this title centered and a different color for the text.

00:06:47.019 --> 00:06:49.260
All right.

00:06:49.299 --> 00:06:53.899
So I would just like to jump right into a coding demo.

00:06:53.899 --> 00:06:59.500
There's this link here if you want to get back to basically the same R script on PositCloud.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:05.100
I do want to highlight the fact that this stuff is very much still in development, especially

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:11.660
the sidebars and accordions are not yet on CRAN, so you have to install from GitHub to

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:13.820
get it.

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:17.820
But I'm actually going to be showing you a branch currently that we don't even have on

00:07:17.859 --> 00:07:18.380
main.

00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:24.100
So there's a couple, like, naming differences that are still very experimental at this

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:24.459
point.

00:07:26.739 --> 00:07:28.100
All right, so.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:38.500
I have this R script here where I'm going to load BSLib and Shiny, and then also for

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:43.220
sake of demonstration, I'm going to use the R package crosstalk, basically so that I

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:47.859
don't have to, like, write a bunch of Shiny code and create a Shiny app for every single

00:07:47.859 --> 00:07:48.459
example.

00:07:48.980 --> 00:07:54.500
So all the examples we're going to see here today are actually there's no Shiny server

00:07:54.500 --> 00:07:55.820
running in the background.

00:07:56.179 --> 00:08:04.540
This is all basically a static website and any sort of, like, filtering between inputs and

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:08.899
outputs is going to be handled purely in the browser via crosstalk.

00:08:09.859 --> 00:08:14.260
And then I'm also going to use Plotly and Leaflet just to have some nice visuals to go

00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:15.140
along with this.

00:08:15.619 --> 00:08:20.500
So I'm going to load all these packages, and then I'm just going to kind of wave over this

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:26.500
setup code here and just kind of mention I'm using crosstalk to create a list of basically,

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:28.459
like, drop-down input controls.

00:08:29.299 --> 00:08:35.260
So just imagine this as, like, an input of, like, select inputs if you're creating a Shiny

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:35.739
app.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:38.099
So I'm going to create these.

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:41.340
I'm also going to create a list of Plotly visuals.

00:08:42.539 --> 00:08:49.260
And all of these filter controls and the plots are going to be using this diamonds dataset.

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:54.539
So I'm going to be able to basically, like, drill down on diamond cut, color, and clarity.

00:08:55.099 --> 00:09:00.059
And then I'm also going to be able to get histograms of, like, the diamond price and the

00:09:00.059 --> 00:09:04.380
diamond carats, as well as counts by cut and clarity.

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:07.979
But the details there are not so important for this.

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:16.059
But I'm also going to use another dataset to also, I'm just going to want to incorporate a

00:09:16.059 --> 00:09:18.619
map eventually in these examples.

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:25.739
So I'm going to create another map just for sake of comparison with the Plotly visuals.

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:32.859
But let's get right into, you know, an example that you, you know, hopefully all of you have

00:09:32.859 --> 00:09:39.340
experienced creating, like, a fixed page with maybe just one output inside of that fixed

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:39.900
page.

00:09:40.619 --> 00:09:48.780
You may have noticed that, you know, things like Plotly or Leaflet or Shiny's plot output,

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:54.380
basically anything that's kind of output-like in Shiny tends to look a little bit like a

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:58.859
Shiny, tends to want to default to a height of 400 pixels.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:06.619
And you might have used something like Shiny's fill page before, which allows you to do

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:07.739
something similar to this.

00:10:07.739 --> 00:10:09.340
It's a little bit more difficult.

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:14.780
But bslib is kind of introducing this concept of a fillable container.

00:10:15.659 --> 00:10:20.460
And a fillable container basically, like, activates what we're calling a fill item.

00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:26.380
So that the fill item is allowed to grow and shrink with the size of that fillable container.

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:35.419
So because page fillable is basically creating this container that's fillable and setting

00:10:35.419 --> 00:10:40.780
its size to the browser window, and there's a fill item inside of that fillable container,

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:46.299
this plot will no longer just always default to a 400 pixel height.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:52.539
It will use the size of its fillable container to decide how large it needs to be.

00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:55.020
All right.

00:10:55.020 --> 00:11:02.059
So now if I put multiple plots in here, inside of this fillable container, these plots are

00:11:02.059 --> 00:11:07.340
allowed to shrink and grow to fit the size of this fillable container.

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:10.059
All right.

00:11:10.059 --> 00:11:13.340
So we're going to, like, return to this idea quite a bit.

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:15.500
So I just want to make a sticky note here.

00:11:16.539 --> 00:11:20.700
About this just kind of reminding us of this terminology here.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:26.700
That a fillable container activates a fill item's ability to grow and shrink.

00:11:27.739 --> 00:11:33.739
And also, we're thinking about kind of outputs in general in a lot of cases, like,

00:11:33.739 --> 00:11:37.419
most HTML widgets, things like shiny plot outputs.

00:11:37.419 --> 00:11:40.539
And also a lot of the components that we see here today

00:11:40.539 --> 00:11:43.260
are going to want to act like fill items by default.

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:46.940
Right?

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:51.580
And I'm also going to use this syntax here quite a bit in some of these examples of this

00:11:51.580 --> 00:12:00.219
triple bang, Rlang's triple bang operator, which this will allow me to basically pass in

00:12:00.219 --> 00:12:05.340
all of the plots in this list of plots as arguments to this page fillable.

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:08.059
So this is equivalent to what we saw up here.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:11.820
All right.

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:13.820
So introducing cards.

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:19.020
If I were to just put a card inside of a page fixed context, it does what you might

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:25.500
think it might do, where it's very similar to before, where I just have a plot that's

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.659
going to default to 400 pixel height.

00:12:28.299 --> 00:12:32.219
But then the card is going to allow me to put, like, a card header.

00:12:32.219 --> 00:12:36.219
So I could put a title above the card body area.

00:12:36.219 --> 00:12:41.500
And then I can use card body to, you know, put some content inside of this card.

00:12:42.219 --> 00:12:50.219
Now, if I just change the page fixed to page fillable, again, we're going to think about

00:12:50.219 --> 00:12:54.299
cards as like, you know, like a fill item, almost like a plot.

00:12:55.900 --> 00:13:02.140
And since this is a fill item going inside of a fillable container, the card itself is

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:08.619
going to be now allowed to determine its size based on whatever the size of the browser

00:13:08.619 --> 00:13:09.179
window is.

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:16.059
So I could even make this very small, and the plot will still do its default 400 pixel

00:13:16.059 --> 00:13:16.380
height.

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:24.380
But the card itself is allowed to determine its size based on the fillable container.

00:13:26.619 --> 00:13:27.020
All right.

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:32.940
So now, you know, if you instead wanted the plot to always match the size of the card

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:38.619
body, you can kind of do the analogous thing at the card body level of saying instead of

00:13:38.619 --> 00:13:43.900
kind of like a paged fixed context where it's not a fillable container, I can make

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:45.820
this a fillable container.

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:53.179
And now the fill item inside of this fillable container is activated to be able to grow

00:13:53.179 --> 00:13:56.140
and shrink to match whatever the size of the card body is.

00:13:59.099 --> 00:13:59.419
All right.

00:13:59.419 --> 00:14:06.059
So now if I wanted to dump multiple plots into this card body, you know, I'm going to

00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:10.299
there's going to be like a lot of stuff to show now inside of this card body.

00:14:10.940 --> 00:14:16.219
So if this card body becomes really small, I might want to say at some point, like once

00:14:16.219 --> 00:14:23.659
this gets to a size that's smaller than 400 pixels, I don't want to allow those plots

00:14:23.659 --> 00:14:26.619
to keep shrinking so that they're like zero height.

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:30.940
So you can do something like I want the minimum height to be 400 pixels.

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:36.859
And now if I have contents that are larger than that 400 pixels, I can just scroll and

00:14:36.859 --> 00:14:39.580
it doesn't shrink to be smaller than that size.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:43.580
All right.

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:50.460
And you might be wondering, like, you know, why do we why are we kind of making this kind

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:56.059
of complicated in the sense that at the component level, we're making you think about fillable

00:14:56.700 --> 00:14:58.460
containers and fill items.

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:06.780
And part of the answer is it gives you a lot of power to do things like combine scrolling

00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:12.780
and fill behavior at a very particular sub region of the UI.

00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:19.020
So I'm going to give you an example here where I just have like the typical page fixed

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:22.700
context and I have a couple cards here.

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:28.299
So since I'm not trying to fill this to the page, they're going to like do their normal

00:15:28.380 --> 00:15:32.780
thing of rendering 400 pixels by default in terms of the height.

00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:39.500
But I'm also going to on each one of these cards add this full screen behavior that when

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:44.940
I now hover on the card body, I'm going to get this icon that says expand, which is short

00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:46.539
for expanding to full screen.

00:15:47.179 --> 00:15:49.739
So I'm going to expand this first card here.

00:15:50.780 --> 00:15:56.859
And when I do this, the card is now going to match whatever the size of the browser

00:15:56.859 --> 00:15:57.500
window is.

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:05.260
And similar to how before, since I have a card body here and not a card body fillable

00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:12.780
container, the plot is just going to render to its default height at 400 pixels and just

00:16:12.780 --> 00:16:18.140
remain at 400 pixels regardless of how big the card body is.

00:16:18.140 --> 00:16:23.020
So I can get real small here and then I need to scroll to get at the entire plot.

00:16:23.900 --> 00:16:31.179
Now, if you contrast this with the card body fillable card here, now if I expand, the plot

00:16:31.179 --> 00:16:34.700
will grow and shrink to match whatever the card body size is here.

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:46.059
Right, so in a lot of cases, if you're using this full screen feature, you're going to

00:16:46.059 --> 00:16:51.340
probably want to pair this with a card body fillable context, especially if you're in

00:16:52.299 --> 00:16:58.700
this kind of scenario where you have like an output visual that you always want to basically

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:01.739
match whatever the size of the card body size is.

00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:09.260
So I'm going to wrap this up into kind of a helper function and also add this utility

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:14.140
class to make the card headers background color to be dark.

00:17:15.099 --> 00:17:22.540
Then I'm going to wrap each one of these plotly plots up into a plot card.

00:17:23.660 --> 00:17:27.260
And then I also just want to mention in general, we're kind of thinking about these

00:17:27.260 --> 00:17:32.619
components as making it easy for you to preview them at the console.

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:42.459
So, you know, you might be used to like printing stuff like div or a Chinese column at the

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:47.819
console and it just prints out the HTML that would eventually go into the page.

00:17:48.780 --> 00:17:54.459
But for these things, you probably, you know, in most cases, want to just preview the results.

00:17:54.459 --> 00:17:58.300
So when you print these things, we'll kind of automatically wrap it up into a page

00:17:58.300 --> 00:17:59.260
container for you.

00:17:59.979 --> 00:18:05.500
So now I can preview the fact that I have a plot card here and I can expand it to full

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:11.420
screen and the plot will grow and shrink to match whatever the card body size is.

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:15.260
All right.

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:25.020
And then we also have like a new way to create kind of like column centric layouts through

00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:26.859
this layout column wrap.

00:18:26.859 --> 00:18:33.420
So kind of think of this in some way as kind of like a modern equivalent to fluid row and

00:18:33.420 --> 00:18:41.420
column in a way that you just want basically the same column size for each one of your

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:41.979
columns.

00:18:43.180 --> 00:18:47.180
There's a lot more to this layout column wrap than I'm going to cover today.

00:18:47.819 --> 00:18:54.619
But just to demonstrate here, you can give this width argument a value like one half

00:18:54.619 --> 00:18:57.339
and that's going to basically give me like a two column layout.

00:18:58.300 --> 00:19:04.859
And in the same way that we're thinking about cards and outputs as fill items by default,

00:19:05.739 --> 00:19:11.020
since this is a fill item, I can put this into a fillable container like page fillable

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:15.099
with another fill item like pay plot counts.

00:19:15.099 --> 00:19:20.060
And now this gives me kind of like a grid like layout where in the first row, I have

00:19:20.060 --> 00:19:25.260
two columns and in the bottom and the second row, I just have something that spans the

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:26.699
full width.

00:19:29.339 --> 00:19:29.579
All right.

00:19:29.579 --> 00:19:38.380
So I'm going to save this result and then feed this into another layout function that

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:41.500
we just added in the development version called layout sidebar.

00:19:42.619 --> 00:19:44.699
And this is also a fill item.

00:19:44.699 --> 00:19:52.619
So if I plop this into a page fillable context, this is going to make it so that

00:19:55.180 --> 00:20:00.780
I have this layout sidebar that's always going to grow and shrink with the size of my browser

00:20:00.780 --> 00:20:01.180
window.

00:20:02.459 --> 00:20:07.099
So notice I have like the sidebar on the left hand side and the main content on the right

00:20:07.099 --> 00:20:07.819
hand side.

00:20:08.380 --> 00:20:10.619
And I can go up and down like this.

00:20:11.180 --> 00:20:16.140
But this collapse toggle is always going to remain constant here towards the bottom of

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:21.979
this layout container where I can toggle the visibility of this sidebar.

00:20:24.459 --> 00:20:29.979
And currently in the viewer, we're not supporting CSS transitions in the way that I'm using

00:20:29.979 --> 00:20:30.459
it here.

00:20:30.459 --> 00:20:36.300
But in a real browser, you would see a transition happening with the collapsing of the sidebar.

00:20:37.739 --> 00:20:39.900
All right.

00:20:39.900 --> 00:20:47.420
So this is kind of like analogous to the card body introduction to the card body context

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:54.219
in the sense that if I think about the main content area here, I've just kind of put in

00:20:54.219 --> 00:20:56.300
a lot of content into this container.

00:20:57.020 --> 00:21:01.020
And I'm allowing it to just kind of render to its default height.

00:21:01.579 --> 00:21:04.939
And then I'm allowed to scroll up and down if there's lots of content.

00:21:05.819 --> 00:21:13.979
But if I wanted to opt into more of like the card body fillable behavior, I can set this

00:21:13.979 --> 00:21:16.540
fillable equal to true on layout sidebar.

00:21:17.099 --> 00:21:19.260
And now it's going to create a fill.

00:21:19.260 --> 00:21:25.260
It's going to treat the main content area as a fillable container so that the fill items

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:31.500
that are going into this container are allowed to activate their ability to grow and shrink.

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:37.500
All right.

00:21:37.500 --> 00:21:44.380
So this ability for layout sidebar to kind of fit to the page is really nice.

00:21:45.260 --> 00:21:51.260
But it's not always going to give us a great user experience, especially if I'm in this

00:21:51.260 --> 00:22:01.420
kind of scenario where maybe I want to add like some more visuals where, you know, these

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:07.260
input controls, I didn't really point this out, but I have this ability to go in and

00:22:07.260 --> 00:22:11.900
change the cut and color and clarity of the diamonds that I'm looking at.

00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:16.060
And that's going to update all of these diamond specific outputs.

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:22.780
But it's not impacting what information is being shown on the map.

00:22:22.780 --> 00:22:24.859
Like this is an entirely different data set.

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:32.219
And these input controls are just not semantically related to this mapping visual.

00:22:34.459 --> 00:22:41.099
So one thing I can do is just pull out the map from the layout sidebar container.

00:22:41.099 --> 00:22:49.420
So at least now there's a better visual grouping of this sidebar layout being more like visually

00:22:49.420 --> 00:22:53.500
closer to the plotly visuals in the main content area.

00:22:54.939 --> 00:23:01.339
But now the map and the map here is just kind of separated out towards the bottom.

00:23:01.339 --> 00:23:05.180
And it's a little bit clearer that these input controls are not related to the map.

00:23:08.060 --> 00:23:08.380
All right.

00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:14.859
So if you're kind of in this situation where you have like input controls that are want

00:23:14.859 --> 00:23:20.060
to be kind of grouped together in different areas of the page, you can leverage the fact

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:23.020
that this layout sidebar integrates nicely with a card.

00:23:23.900 --> 00:23:29.420
So I can use the same card API and just kind of drop in a layout sidebar similar to how

00:23:29.420 --> 00:23:31.099
I would with like a card body.

00:23:32.060 --> 00:23:38.699
And now if I print this out and preview it, I've actually also specified that I actually

00:23:38.699 --> 00:23:41.500
don't want the sidebar to be open by default.

00:23:42.140 --> 00:23:44.140
So it's going to be closed.

00:23:44.140 --> 00:23:49.660
But I can go here to the lower left hand corner and toggle the sidebar to be open.

00:23:50.219 --> 00:23:55.739
And now I have a filter that's specific to this map all wrapped into a card that I could

00:23:55.739 --> 00:23:57.739
plop into a larger page.

00:24:00.300 --> 00:24:00.619
All right.

00:24:00.619 --> 00:24:06.459
So let's kind of combine these two where I'm going to take this basically the same layout

00:24:06.459 --> 00:24:08.459
sidebar diamonds example.

00:24:09.579 --> 00:24:13.020
And I'm going to feed that into a page of a navbar page.

00:24:13.979 --> 00:24:20.140
And not only that, but I'm going to basically ask this navbar page to make the diamonds

00:24:20.140 --> 00:24:24.780
page fillable, make a fillable container just for the diamonds page.

00:24:25.579 --> 00:24:29.339
And then I'm going to have a separate page for the map with the earthquakes data.

00:24:31.099 --> 00:24:31.900
Open this here.

00:24:34.140 --> 00:24:41.979
And, you know, now I have this nice, you know, kind of global sidebar that's only here when

00:24:42.459 --> 00:24:43.979
I'm on the diamonds page.

00:24:43.979 --> 00:24:48.140
And on the earthquakes page, the sidebar is no longer relevant.

00:24:49.900 --> 00:24:56.540
And I've basically scoped these sidebars in this case to this specific card.

00:24:57.339 --> 00:25:01.020
And on this page, scoped just to this page.

00:25:01.579 --> 00:25:01.979
All right.

00:25:01.979 --> 00:25:07.819
Now, if you want more of like the shiny dashboard kind of thing where it assumes that you want

00:25:08.780 --> 00:25:15.099
kind of a singular sidebar that's shared across every page, then you can do something like

00:25:15.099 --> 00:25:20.699
this where you can provide the sidebar argument or sorry, the sidebar object to the sidebar

00:25:20.699 --> 00:25:21.260
argument.

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:27.099
And, you know, if you are in this kind of scenario where you have a lot of sidebars

00:25:27.339 --> 00:25:32.060
and, you know, if you are in this kind of scenario where you have some input controls

00:25:32.060 --> 00:25:39.260
that are truly relevant and truly affect the data being shown on each page, then, you know,

00:25:39.260 --> 00:25:42.060
maybe you want this kind of functionality.

00:25:44.699 --> 00:25:53.020
And just to point out, you can also like maybe in this situation, you know, you do want a

00:25:53.020 --> 00:25:59.260
shared sidebar, but you actually want this to be part of maybe a larger page.

00:25:59.819 --> 00:26:03.500
You can just change the page nav bar to nav's tab card.

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:10.939
And now you have this shared sidebar across multiple pages, but now sitting inside of

00:26:10.939 --> 00:26:15.420
a card that you could then put into a larger page if you wanted to.

00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:20.300
All right.

00:26:20.300 --> 00:26:26.300
And then we also pretty quickly here, I think I'm kind of running out of time, but we've

00:26:26.300 --> 00:26:29.420
also added value boxes in bslib.

00:26:29.420 --> 00:26:37.900
So, these are pretty similar to what you would get with Shiny dashboard and flex dashboard,

00:26:38.619 --> 00:26:42.619
but it is a little bit more extensible and flexible.

00:26:43.339 --> 00:26:50.060
And so, you have this ability to like we basically give you like a showcase slot is what we call

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:50.540
it.

00:26:50.540 --> 00:26:54.459
And you can put any sort of HTML object inside of here.

00:26:54.459 --> 00:26:59.579
So, you could actually put like HTML widgets and, you know, other stuff.

00:26:59.579 --> 00:27:05.660
But here I'm using this BS icons package, which gives you icons that look like are

00:27:05.660 --> 00:27:06.939
designed for Bootstrap.

00:27:08.459 --> 00:27:11.339
And then also like customized colors and stuff like that.

00:27:12.619 --> 00:27:19.660
But if you're interested in like doing more sophisticated stuff like with this, you can

00:27:19.660 --> 00:27:24.780
just like with cards, say value box full screen equal to true and then have like a little

00:27:24.780 --> 00:27:30.300
spark line inside of this card that when you expand it becomes more of a full view.

00:27:30.859 --> 00:27:35.819
And I have a link here to some documentation with some examples of this kind of idea.

00:27:35.819 --> 00:27:39.660
All right.

00:27:39.660 --> 00:27:42.699
We're also adding accordions in the development version.

00:27:42.699 --> 00:27:49.500
So, here I'm going to use accordions and plop an accordion inside of the sidebar where this

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:55.979
can be a really convenient way if you have tons of input controls and there's maybe groups

00:27:55.979 --> 00:27:57.660
of related input controls.

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:04.619
You can group them together and then also maybe hide groups of input controls if they're

00:28:04.619 --> 00:28:11.900
not quite as important as other ones and allow the user to kind of, you know, be able

00:28:11.900 --> 00:28:15.660
to navigate a lot of input controls a little bit more effectively.

00:28:18.219 --> 00:28:21.819
You can also use accordions in kind of more of a standalone fashion.

00:28:21.819 --> 00:28:25.099
So, I don't necessarily have to put them inside of a sidebar.

00:28:25.099 --> 00:28:28.939
I can just have like sections of pros if I wanted.

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:36.859
And then I also just wanted to kind of as a side note mention, I recently, this is on

00:28:36.859 --> 00:28:43.739
my personal GitHub repo, but I created this histo slider package that gives you a slider

00:28:43.739 --> 00:28:47.739
control that allows you to have like a histogram tied to it.

00:28:48.300 --> 00:28:54.140
So, I can see on this slider here it's telling me like most of the diamonds are like lower

00:28:54.140 --> 00:28:56.540
than a carat or a carat and a half.

00:28:56.540 --> 00:29:03.900
But then if I filter on maybe diamonds that are a carat or more, you can see that, you

00:29:03.900 --> 00:29:10.300
know, obviously diamonds that have a lot of carats are more expensive.

00:29:10.939 --> 00:29:16.859
So, you can, you know, filter on like a carat or more and be aware that there aren't a lot

00:29:16.859 --> 00:29:21.260
of diamonds that are a carat or more, but they're, you know, more expensive.

00:29:21.420 --> 00:29:21.979
All right.

00:29:21.979 --> 00:29:23.180
So, that's the demo.

00:29:25.500 --> 00:29:32.939
And just to summarize quickly here, so, this toolkit that we're building out in BSLib,

00:29:32.939 --> 00:29:37.500
obviously, it's kind of a steeper learning curve than Shiny Dashboard and Flex Dashboard,

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:46.300
which kind of limits you in a way that is useful, but when you want to like kind of go

00:29:46.540 --> 00:29:51.900
beyond sort of the templates that it provides you, it's really hard to go beyond that.

00:29:52.619 --> 00:29:56.859
So, there are benefits to kind of using this more flexible model.

00:29:56.859 --> 00:29:59.579
It's going to allow you to do more stuff with theming.

00:30:00.219 --> 00:30:04.380
It's going to allow you to compose stuff a lot better and extend things and port them

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:05.420
to other projects.

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:11.260
And you may miss some Shiny Dashboard features.

00:30:11.260 --> 00:30:15.819
I could get into this, but for sake of time, I don't think I will.

00:30:16.939 --> 00:30:19.260
But as always, we love to hear your feedback.

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:24.540
If you're trying to like port a Shiny Dashboard project to using BSLib, I would love to know

00:30:25.099 --> 00:30:27.739
how that goes and if you have ideas for improvements.

00:30:29.579 --> 00:30:35.579
And also, just remind you that not everything really needs to be a dashboard and or use Shiny.

00:30:35.979 --> 00:30:43.420
So, we've designed these UI components so that you can use them in our markdown, use

00:30:43.420 --> 00:30:46.060
them to create static sites like we saw today.

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:52.219
As of today, I don't think you can really use these in a seamless way with Quarto, but

00:30:52.219 --> 00:30:57.979
hopefully that's coming down the pipeline and that you can kind of use these components

00:30:57.979 --> 00:31:01.339
to, you know, do more than just create a dashboard.

00:31:01.660 --> 00:31:05.099
And just as a reminder, this stuff is still in development.

00:31:05.099 --> 00:31:11.339
So, only try this out if you're, you know, not trying to ship stuff to production.

00:31:11.339 --> 00:31:14.540
So, but hopefully we'll see a release in the next few weeks.

00:31:17.260 --> 00:31:20.699
And that is all I have for today.

00:31:20.699 --> 00:31:28.859
If you'd like to learn more, go to rstudio.github.io slash BSLib and expect some documentation

00:31:29.180 --> 00:31:31.739
improvements in the coming weeks.

00:31:32.300 --> 00:31:36.540
But at least we do at the moment, we have, you know, an article on sidebars if you're

00:31:36.540 --> 00:31:37.660
interested in seeing that.

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:42.699
It is on the development version, but at least we have some writing about it and some examples.

00:31:43.500 --> 00:31:47.739
Again, the link to the cloud project and some links to my personal stuff.

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:51.579
And that's all I have.

00:31:52.300 --> 00:31:52.800
Thank you.

00:31:53.819 --> 00:31:56.540
Thank you so much, Carson, for that wonderful presentation.

00:31:56.540 --> 00:31:58.780
And I think the Histo slider took me away.

00:31:58.780 --> 00:31:59.900
It's very, very cool.

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:03.579
And it reminded me of, you know, when you're browsing datasets on Kaggle, you actually

00:32:03.579 --> 00:32:06.060
see something like that, but it's not that interactive.

00:32:06.060 --> 00:32:08.859
And this is just on another level, absolutely.

00:32:09.579 --> 00:32:11.739
We have some questions from the audience.

00:32:11.739 --> 00:32:14.300
So, I'll just walk you through them quickly.

00:32:14.939 --> 00:32:19.819
So, from Logan, we have, what about ensuring that all the plots in a fluid row are the

00:32:19.819 --> 00:32:21.739
same height using the fillable logics?

00:32:21.979 --> 00:32:22.479
Yeah.

00:32:22.540 --> 00:32:30.380
So, I would say at least for now, it's probably going to be a better experience to use this

00:32:30.380 --> 00:32:31.420
layout column wrap.

00:32:32.219 --> 00:32:38.219
So, it's going to be a little bit painful, and hopefully we do a good job of explaining

00:32:38.219 --> 00:32:40.060
this kind of thing in the documentation.

00:32:41.020 --> 00:32:45.339
It's not quite there yet, but we're kind of working on this of, you know, what if you

00:32:45.339 --> 00:32:49.099
want to use a UI that's not in VS lib to do things like layout?

00:32:49.339 --> 00:32:55.500
There will be ways to do it, but it will be more seamless if you use something like layout

00:32:55.500 --> 00:32:56.060
column wrap.

00:32:57.099 --> 00:33:03.819
And, you know, layout column wrap is kind of optimized for assuming that you have equal

00:33:03.819 --> 00:33:04.859
width columns.

00:33:05.579 --> 00:33:10.140
But if you do want columns with differing widths, that is still possible using layout

00:33:10.140 --> 00:33:10.699
column wrap.

00:33:10.699 --> 00:33:18.140
So, it's, yeah, it's hard to say, like, layout column wrap is the best way to do it.

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:22.140
I would say, like, layout column wrap is going to supersede fluid row and column at

00:33:22.140 --> 00:33:22.699
this point.

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:30.699
But if you do really want this filling behavior, I would say, like, very much try to avoid

00:33:31.500 --> 00:33:33.180
using, like, fluid row and column.

00:33:35.660 --> 00:33:35.979
Great.

00:33:35.979 --> 00:33:37.579
I think that would answer the question.

00:33:37.579 --> 00:33:43.020
And we have another question from David who asks, how does layout column wrap and other

00:33:43.020 --> 00:33:45.979
fillable containers relate to the CSS flexbox?

00:33:46.939 --> 00:33:50.380
So, a fillable container is a flexbox container.

00:33:50.380 --> 00:33:59.339
So, if you know flexbox, a fillable container is a flexbox container, and the fill items

00:33:59.339 --> 00:34:02.619
are basically, like, flex1.

00:34:02.619 --> 00:34:06.060
Like, it's a flex item with the ability to grow and shrink.

00:34:06.699 --> 00:34:12.699
So, if you do know flexbox and are comfortable with it, you can, you know, of course, use

00:34:12.780 --> 00:34:19.179
fillable and fill concepts, but then you can also, like, kind of add inline styles or more

00:34:19.179 --> 00:34:22.860
CSS to get more particular with the behavior that you want.

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:28.939
If, like, the kind of abstraction that we provided that's hopefully a lot simpler than

00:34:28.939 --> 00:34:34.459
working with flexbox directly doesn't quite fit your use case, then you can just kind

00:34:34.459 --> 00:34:36.459
of tack on more CSS as you need.

00:34:36.620 --> 00:34:41.500
And I think the last question that we have is from David, who asks, can you relate or

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:45.020
connect the charts in such a way that they interact with each other?

00:34:45.020 --> 00:34:49.820
So, for example, if you put an input in one, it kind of reflects on the other visualizations

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:50.379
as well.

00:34:50.379 --> 00:34:52.939
Is something like that available or planned?

00:34:52.939 --> 00:34:53.979
What would you say on that?

00:34:53.979 --> 00:35:00.379
Well, yeah, I mean, if I understand the question directly, like, that's kind of what we were

00:35:00.780 --> 00:35:07.820
showing here today with those drop-down input controls, changing values there was updating

00:35:07.820 --> 00:35:08.620
the outputs.

00:35:08.620 --> 00:35:09.179
Yeah.

00:35:09.179 --> 00:35:14.860
And that was working through crosstalk, and there are certainly limitations to what you

00:35:14.860 --> 00:35:16.780
can do with just crosstalk.

00:35:16.780 --> 00:35:21.500
So, when you want to do stuff that's a little bit more sophisticated, then you might need

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:22.620
to reach for Shiny.

00:35:23.419 --> 00:35:30.939
And, I mean, I will just kind of drop a hint at this point that that's a pretty high-priority

00:35:30.939 --> 00:35:37.179
item for us is to actually kind of come back and revisit crosstalk and think about it now

00:35:37.179 --> 00:35:44.379
that we're heading in a direction of being able to run stuff purely in the browser.

00:35:44.540 --> 00:35:51.260
We might be thinking about, you know, basically revisiting the concept of crosstalk and leveraging

00:35:51.260 --> 00:35:58.139
something like WebR to power, you know, these kind of connected multiple views in a way

00:35:58.139 --> 00:36:04.060
that you can still write R code and, like, have your server functions customizing how

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:08.699
these views are actually connected together, but in a way that ultimately, like, runs in

00:36:08.699 --> 00:36:09.419
the browser.

00:36:09.580 --> 00:36:14.699
So, that's kind of on our roadmap to investigate that a little more.

00:36:14.699 --> 00:36:16.219
I think that's good to hear.

00:36:16.219 --> 00:36:18.379
As long as it's on the roadmap, we'll know.

00:36:18.379 --> 00:36:22.060
And thank you so much again, Carson, for this wonderful tutorial and talk.

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:24.780
And thank you, and we'll see you next year.

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:25.580
Yeah, thank you.

